<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PERU </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Say SL `Definitely Split' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Say SL `Definitely Split' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2904131794 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1751 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2904131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 28 Apr (EFE) -- The Peruvian police guarantee 
that the Shining Path [SL] terrorist group has split. In a 
report released today by the Counterterrorism Directorate, the 
police speculate on the possibility of a clash between the two 
factions into which the group has allegedly split. 
  The report states that the leaders who support peace -- 
which 
government officials believe is led by Abimael Guzman, the SL 
founder and leader -- have been expelled. The other faction 
does not regard him as a leader -- although it recognizes him as 
"ideologist" -- because he "does not address (the party or the 
war) from jail." 
  Government officials believe the faction that does not 
accept 
Guzman's leadership believes the alleged peace proposal is not 
genuine, they consider it a government "hoax." 
  The police report points out that the group split after the 
establishment -- under the leadership of Oscar Ramirez Durand, 
alias "Feliciano" -- of a new central committee in March in the 
Huanta Province mountains. This new central committee agreed to 
pursue the war that began in 1980. 
  The police report states that this group described the 
members of the central committee allegedly headed by Guzman as 
"debased people, traitors, weaklings, and old revisionists." 
  Government officials state that the rejoinder issued by 
Guzman's loyal followers was disclosed in a communique also 
dated March. In this communique, Guzman's loyal followers 
charge the rebels with feigning loyalty to their leader and with 
"undermining the party" over "personal and opportunist 
ambitions." 
  Therefore, the police believe "the internal dispute has 
entered the elimination phase and a settlement of accounts has 
not been ruled out." 

</TEXT>

