<F P=100> NEAR EAST/SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> EGYPT </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nasirite, Jihad Inmates Separated Due to `Close Ties' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nasirite, Jihad Inmates Separated Due to `Close Ties' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2704110794 Beirut AL-SAFIR in Arabic 22 Apr 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> NC2704110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut AL-SAFIR </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Amr Nasif from Cairo] </F>
  [Excerpt] In the past few days, Turah prison wardens have 
separated Mahmud Nur-al-Din, leader of the Nasirite group 
Egypt's Revolution, from 'Abbud-al-Zumur, leader of the al-Jihad 
Organization. 
  Both men are serving life sentences: Nur-al-Din for his 
leadership of Egypt's Revolution, a group that between 1986 and 
1988 killed Israeli elements and people working for the Mosad in 
Cairo; and Al-Zumur for his involvement in the assassination of 
President Anwar al-Sadat. 
  Security sources attribute this move to the close ties that 
had recently grown between Nur-al-Din and al-Zumur, culminating 
in their agreement to alternate in leading the inmates in 
prayers. 
  Nur-al-Din has won the confidence of al-Jihad inmates in 
Turah jail. The prisoners treat him as a spiritual father. 
Those on death row have a long meeting with him before their 
execution and sometimes scribble a note of gratitude on a scrap 
of their clothes for him to keep as a souvenir. Nur-al-Din, for 
his part, normally leads the prayer for the absent--a memorial 
service for the executed al-Jihad members. 
  Nur-al-Din has issued a call to the Islamic Group and the 
al-Jihad Organization through AL-SAFIR, asking them to attack 
Israeli targets and interests in Egypt instead of the Egyptian 
police, tourism, and banks. [passage omitted recapping recent 
terrorist incidents] 

</TEXT>

