<DATE1>   5 May 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> FBIS TERRORISM REPORT HIGHLIGHTS: 26 April-2 May </F>
<H3> <TI>   FBIS TERRORISM REPORT HIGHLIGHTS: 26 April-2 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FBIS TERRORISM REPORT HIGHLIGHTS: 26 April-2 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   11111111 </F>
<F P=103> 11111111 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
CSO 

    Editor's Note: The FBIS Terrorism Desk welcomes 
subscribers' comments and suggestions at (703) 733-5512. 
  Highlights and major incidents in this edition of 
the FBIS Terrorism Report include: 
<H5>  Argentina </H5>
  Buenos Aires police raided a right-wing military training 
camp on an island in Tigre District, seizing explosives and 
medium weapons. A police chief said that the camp probably 
belonged to the "Painted Faces" group, who were training to free 
former coup-plotter Seineldin from prison. 
<H5>  Colombia/U.S. </H5>
  Just before the New York trial of Dandenys Munoz Mosquera, 
a.k.a. La Quica, a Colombian informant "with a great deal of 
credibility" has said that La Quica was a leading figure in the 
1989 Avianca airlines bombing, taking orders from Carlos Mario 
Alzate Urquijo, a.k.a. El Arete. 
<H5>  Iran/International </H5>
  London's THE SUNDAY TIMES publishes a report on a November 
1993 "terrorist summit" in Tehran, which it says was held to 
plan operations in European capitals. 
<H5>  Lebanon/Germany </H5>
  The Hammadi family told AL-HAYAH newspaper that press 
reports that 'Abbas Hammadi is in Germany trying to break his 
brother out of prison are "completely wrong." 
<H5>  Libya/Germany </H5>
  Germany is investigating the mid-April death of a 
counterterrorism officer from the Federal Office for the 
Protection of the Constitution while on vacation in Libya. 
<H5>  Peru </H5>
  According to Madrid's EFE news service, the alias "Ricardo 
Z" has appeared as the new leader of the Shining Path. The 
Counterterrorism Department speculates that Ricardo Z could be a 
new figure, or merely a new alias for Oscar Alberto Ramirez, 
a.k.a "Feliciano." 
<H5>  Ukraine/Russia </H5>
  Security officers in Mariupol arrested several "foreign 
citizens" who had built an explosive device, intending to use it 
against an unspecified embassy in Moscow. 
<H5>  SELECTED VIDEO REPORTS </H5>
  Video coverage will resume with the next issue of the 
Terrorism Report. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

