<H3> <TI>   Explanation Sought on German Terrorism Expert's Death in </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Explanation Sought on German Terrorism Expert's Death in </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Libya 

<F P=102>   LD2804143594 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1326 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2804143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN): The death of an employee at the 
Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution and his 
wife during a holiday in Libya has still not been cleared up. 
The case was discussed by the Bundestag Parliamentary Control 
Commission (PKK) today, its chairman Johannes Gerster said 
afterwards. The German Government has briefed the Commission 
about the "brutal" circumstances of the death of the two 
Germans. The control commission strongly criticized the fact 
that the Libyan Government has still not complied with a German 
Government demand that the incident be completely cleared up 
with a comprehensive report. 
  According to press reports, the employee was section leader 
in department six of the Cologne-based Office for the Protection 
of the Constitution, a department which deals with extremist 
acts by foreigners and international terrorism. He is said to 
have died in a military hospital in Tripoli in mid-April. 
According to the reports, the "Middle East and North African 
expert" had a holiday trip to Egypt authorized by his employers. 
There was a ban on travel to Libya at the Office for the 
Protection of the Constitution. 

</TEXT>

