<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   5 May 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PERU </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Insurgent Activities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Insurgent Activities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2904184394 </F>
<F P=103> PY2904184394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on insurgent activities in Peru compiled from Peruvian 
media monitored through 24 April: 
  On 14 April the Counterterrorism Directorate, Dincote, 
presented to the press nine members of the People's Aid faction 
of the Shining Path, SL. They were involved in many attacks 
perpetrated between March 1993 and March 1994. (Lima EL PERUANO 
in Spanish 15 April Political Section p A2) 
  Railway Police Unit personnel deactivated approximately 
eight 
metric tonnes of dynamite that were planted along several 
segments of the Central railway linking Lima with La Oroya. 
(Lima LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 15 Apr 94 p 15) 
  A total of 10 SL "terrorists" died and three Army soldiers 
were wounded in two separate clashes in the township of Moyuna, 
Leoncio Prado Province, on 8 April, and in the township of El 
Salvador, Huallaga Front on 12 April. (Lima EL COMERCIO in 
Spanish 16 Apr 94 p A12) 
  Dincote personnel arrested 19 peddlers in markets located in 
La Victoria and El Agustino Districts. They are members of a SL 
commando that perpetrated selective murders, sabotage, and other 
crimes. (Lima LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 15 Apr 94 p 15) 
  On 15 April, two SL "terrorists" shot dead champion boxer 
Carlos Lavalle Gonzales who lived in La Raucana neighborhood in 
Lima. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 16 Apr 94 p A12) 
  A SL group on 11 April killed three residents of the 
township 
of Sonomoro, 51 km from Satipo Province, Huancayo Department. 
(Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 17 Apr 94 p A16) 
  On 15 April, some 30 SL "terrorists" killed San Juan de 
Lucanas Mayor Teobaldino Huarcaya Berrocal and peasant patrol 
member Jose Quispe, and burned the city hall and an educational 
building in the township of San Juan de Lucana, Ayacucho 
Department. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 18 Apr 94 p A15) 
  On 16 April National Police personnel arrested three SL 
"subversives" in La Victoria District, in Lima. They carried a 
large quantity of subversive propaganda and red flags bearing 
the hammer and sickle. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 18 Apr 94 p A16) 
  SL "terrorists" on 16 April killed 18 people in Monterrico, 
Mazamari District, Satipo Province, Junin Department, because 
they refused to continue cooperating with them. (Lima EL 
COMERCIO in Spanish 19 Apr 94 p A8) 
  A total of 20 SL "terrorists" have surrendered to Army 
troops 
to avail themselves of the repentance law since the so-called 
Operacion Monzon begun early in April in Huanuco Department. 
(Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 20 Apr 94 p A3) 
  On 10 April, Dincote personnel arrested the Tupac Amaru 
Revolutionary Movement, MRTA, third-in-command in the northern 
part of the country. The identity of the "terrorist" and the 
place where he was detained have not been disclosed. (Lima EL 
COMERCIO in Spanish 20 Apr 94 p A12) 
  The Cajamarca National Police Unit presented Lupita Virginia 
Ruiz Paredes, aka Maritza, to the press. She is believed to be 
one of the SL military commands in the Cajabamba, San Marcos, 
and Celendin troubled zones. (Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 21 Apr 
94 p A13) 
  General Alfredo Rodriguez, Huanuco Department Political 
Military commander, has charged the SL with kidnapping 54 
civilians from a village near the township of Moena, in Huallaga 
zone, Leoncio Prado Province. He also reported that 28 other SL 
members surrendered to Army patrols to avail themselves of the 
repentance law. Daniel Espichan, special prosecutor for 
terrorist crimes, said there are currently 4,000 repentants. On 
21 April, MRTA members killed three soldiers and nine peasants 
during an ambush in the Peruvian central jungle. The bodies of 
two of the four miners kidnapped by SL members in San Juan de 
Lucanas on 17 April were found in Ayacucho. (Madrid EFE in 
Spanish 1635 GMT 23 Apr 94) 
  Army forces have rescued approximately 100 Ashaninkas 
Indians 
from seven SL camps located in villages of the jungle province 
of Satipo, Junin Department. They also seized weapons, 
explosives, ammunition, communication equipment, and subversive 
propaganda. The Lima media reports that the security forces 
dismantled a SL column known as the "Red Sea Battalion" in 
Leoncio Prado Province, Huanuco Department. (Madrid EFE in 
Spanish 2053 GMT 24 Apr 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

